A graph database (Graph DB) is a type of database designed to store, manage, and query relationships efficiently.

Instead of tables (rows & columns), it uses a graph structure.

ðŸ”¹ Core Concepts

A graph DB is built on 3 main elements:

1ï¸âƒ£ Nodes (Vertices)

Represent entities

Examples:

User

Product

City

Account

(User)
(Product)

2ï¸âƒ£ Edges (Relationships)

Represent connections between nodes

Are first-class citizens (very important)

Can have direction and meaning

Examples:

USER â†’ BOUGHT â†’ PRODUCT

USER â†’ FRIEND_OF â†’ USER

CITY â†’ LOCATED_IN â†’ COUNTRY

(User)-[FRIEND_OF]->(User)

3ï¸âƒ£ Properties

Keyâ€“value data attached to nodes or edges

Example:

(User {name: "Shoaib", age: 24})

ðŸ”¹ How Itâ€™s Different from SQL Databases
Relational DB (MySQL, PostgreSQL)

Uses tables

Relationships via foreign keys

Complex joins get slow

SELECT *
FROM users
JOIN friends ON users.id = friends.user_id;

Graph DB

Relationships are stored directly

Traversing connections is very fast

No expensive joins

MATCH (u:User)-[:FRIEND_OF]->(f)
RETURN f

